In React, a component re-renders whenever its props change. When you pass an inline object as a prop, if the object itself changes (i.e., any of its properties are updated), the component will re-render because the reference to the object has changed.

To prevent a component from re-rendering when passing an inline object as a prop, you can use one of the following strategies:

1. **Use `React.memo`**: This higher-order component (HOC) memoizes a component and only re-renders it if its props have changed. It is particularly useful for functional components.

   ```jsx
   import React from 'react';

   const MyComponent = React.memo(({ data }) => {
     console.log('Rendering MyComponent');
     return <div>{data.name}</div>;
   });

   function App() {
     const [state, setState] = React.useState({ name: 'Alice' });

     return (
       <div>
         <MyComponent data={state} />
         <button onClick={() => setState({ ...state, name: 'Bob' })}>
           Change Name
         </button>
       </div>
     );
   }

   export default App;
   ```

2. **Use `useMemo`**: This hook can be used to memoize a value that depends on other values and only recompute it when those dependencies change.

   ```jsx
   import React, { useMemo } from 'react';

   const MyComponent = ({ data }) => {
     console.log('Rendering MyComponent');
     return <div>{data.name}</div>;
   };

   function App() {
     const [state, setState] = React.useState({ name: 'Alice' });

     // Use useMemo to memoize the object
     const memoizedData = useMemo(() => ({ ...state }), [state]);

     return (
       <div>
         <MyComponent data={memoizedData} />
         <button onClick={() => setState({ ...state, name: 'Bob' })}>
           Change Name
         </button>
       </div>
     );
   }

   export default App;
   ```

3. **Use `useCallback`**: This hook can be used to memoize a function that depends on other values and only recompute it when those dependencies change.

   ```jsx
   import React, { useCallback } from 'react';

   const MyComponent = ({ data }) => {
     console.log('Rendering MyComponent');
     return <div>{data.name}</div>;
   };

   function App() {
     const [state, setState] = React.useState({ name: 'Alice' });

     // Use useCallback to memoize the function
     const handleNameChange = useCallback(() => {
       setState({ ...state, name: 'Bob' });
     }, [setState]);

     return (
       <div>
         <MyComponent data={state} />
         <button onClick={handleNameChange}>Change Name</button>
       </div>
     );
   }

   export default App;
   ```

By using these techniques, you can prevent a component from re-rendering when passing an inline object as a prop by ensuring that the reference to the object does not change.

